The other option, which still involves a modification to core.js, is to change from using DOM-ready to using a custom "event" of sorts. For instance, you might do something like this:

```
<script src="lab.js"></script>
<script>
$LAB.setOptions({AlwaysPreserveOrder:true})
  .script("jquery.js")
  .script("core.js")
  /*
   inside of core.js, at the end, do:
   $(document).bind("scripts-ready", function(){
     for each (List as f): run f();
   });
  */
  .wait(function(){ List.F1 = ... })
  .wait(function(){ List.F2 = ... })
  .wait(function(){
    $(document).trigger("scripts-ready");
  })
;
</script>
```

In this way, you're using a custom event specifically for the purpose of indicating when scripts are done loading, rather than relying on the conflation with the DOM-ready event.

